Category: Ideas
Author: @BittuChan
Timestamp: March 15, 2026
Body:
 The Problem

  One of the most common validation patterns in real-world apps is cross-field validation — things like "confirm password must match password" or "end date must be
  after start date." In Zod v3, ctx.parent made this possible inside .superRefine(), but in v4 it was removed without a direct replacement.

  This has left a gap that's hitting a lot of developers, especially those using form libraries like React Hook Form, where field-level validation is the standard
  approach.

  Currently the workarounds are:
  - Moving validation to the parent object level — but this breaks form-per-field error mapping
  - Duplicating logic outside Zod — defeats the purpose of a single source of truth for validation
  - Using .pipe() chains — adds complexity for something that should be straightforward

  What I'd Like to See

  A first-class API for accessing sibling field values during field-level refinement. Something like:

  const schema = z.object({
    password: z.string().min(8),
    confirmPassword: z.string().refine(
      (val, ctx) => val === ctx.sibling("password"),
      { message: "Passwords don't match" }
    ),
  });

  Or alternatively, a dependsOn modifier:

  const schema = z.object({
    startDate: z.date(),
    endDate: z.date().dependsOn("startDate", (end, start) => end > start, {
      message: "End date must be after start date",
    }),
  });

  Why This Matters

  - Password confirmation, date ranges, conditional required fields — these aren't edge cases, they're everyday patterns
  - Form libraries map errors by field path — parent-level refinements break that mapping
  - Zod positions itself as the single source of truth for validation and types — cross-field validation is a core part of that story"},{"type":"text","text":"  - Multiple open issues (#5706, #5707) show this is a real pain point across the community

Comments:

    Comment #1 from @manimovassagh on March 20, 2026:

    The removal of `ctx.parent` in v4 definitely left a gap here. The cleanest approach right now is `.superRefine()` at the object level with `path` to attach errors to the correct field:

```ts
const signupSchema = z
  .object({
    password: z.string().min(8),
    confirmPassword: z.string(),
  })
  .superRefine((data, ctx) => {
    if (data.password !== data.confirmPassword) {
      ctx.addIssue({
        code: z.ZodIssueCode.custom,
        message: "Passwords must match",
        path: ["confirmPassword"],
      });
    }
  });
```

With React Hook Form + `@hookform/resolvers/zod`, this maps correctly to field-level errors:

```tsx
const { formState: { errors } } = useForm({ resolver: zodResolver(signupSchema) });
// errors.confirmPassword.message => "Passwords must match"
```

The key insight is `path: ["confirmPassword"]` — RHF resolves errors by path, so even though the refinement lives on the parent, the error shows up on the right field.

Same pattern for date ranges:

```ts
const dateRangeSchema = z
  .object({
    startDate: z.coerce.date(),
    endDate: z.coerce.date(),
  })
  .superRefine((data, ctx) => {
    if (data.endDate <= data.startDate) {
      ctx.addIssue({
        code: z.ZodIssueCode.custom,
        message: "End date must be after start date",
        path: ["endDate"],
      });
    }
  });
```

Agreed that a first-class `.dependsOn()` or `ctx.sibling()` API would be better DX long term. But `.superRefine()` with explicit `path` does work well today and integrates cleanly with form libraries.
