<!-- Answer -->"},{"type":"text","text":"
You're right that the docs don't explicitly state this is "by design," but the current behavior is consistent with Zod's instance-based metadata model and the direction described by @colinhacks. Metadata from `.meta()` is exported by `z.toJSONSchema` as plain properties, but `z.fromJSONSchema` does not restore or register these fields—only standard fields like `description` and `default` are mapped back, and all other metadata is ignored. This asymmetry is intentional: Zod's maintainers have clarified that full round-trip fidelity (including metadata and registry state) is not a design goal, mainly because Zod's type system and metadata model don't map 1:1 with JSON Schema, and deserialization is considered out of scope for now ([see discussion](https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/issues/4781)).

If you need to persist metadata, the recommended approach is to manage it externally and reapply it after deserialization. There are community discussions about using custom properties or vendor extensions, but these aren't implemented in Zod and would require custom logic ([docs](https://zod.dev/metadata), [docs](https://zod.dev/json-schema)).

Your feedback about the inconsistency is valid and has come up in other threads. If round-trip metadata preservation is important for your use case, feel free to share more details or propose it as a feature—I'm happy to relay it to @colinhacks.


