Comment #6 by @colinhacks:

There is absolutely no guarantee of round-trip fidelity. That's just not workable for Zod. Zod doesn't have an equivalent concept for all JSON Schema concepts, and JSON Schema certainly doesn't have a representation for all Zod concepts. Everything here is best-effort. But if you need that level of fidelity, JSON Schema should be your source of truth, and you should use `z.fromJSONSchema()` in both places. 

...though in this scenario it definitely makes more sense just to codegen Zod schemas from JSON Schema (unless the JSON Schema is dynamic?). These are all reasons why I held out on `z.fromJSONSchema()`. If it proves to be a bottomless maintenence burden & source of footguns then I will remove it. There are many rough edges that are not solvable given the impedance mismatch here.

That said I think some solution of metadata is workable. Open to a PR.

"}],"type":"content"},"title":"Metadata persistence and Global Registry support in toJSONSchema / fromJSONSchema round-trip","context":null,"record_type":"github_issue","url":"https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/issues/5564"},{"type":"document","source":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Access nested metadata in zod4?
Category: General
Author: @florianmartens
Timestamp: July 17, 2025
Body:
I have the following nested schema:

```ts
const filterRegistry = z.registry<FilterMetadata>();

const nested = z
    .object({
      include: z
        .array(z.string())
        .max(200)
        .optional(),
      exclude: z
        .array(z.string())
        .max(200)
        .optional(),
    });
filterRegistry.add(nested, {type: "select"})

const schema = z
  .object({
    firstname: nested,
    secondName: nested,
})
```

Ideally I'm looking for a way to retrieve an array of the top level nested metadata like: 

```ts
[{type "select"}, {type: "select"}]
```

Is that possible? 
Comments:

    Comment #1 from @dosubot on July 17, 2025:

    <!-- Answer -->
Yes, you can retrieve an array of metadata for each top-level property by iterating over the object schema's shape and querying the registry for each property's schema instance. In your example, since both `firstname` and `secondName` use the same `nested` schema instance, you'll get the same metadata object for both fields.

Here's how you can do it:

```ts
const shape = schema.shape;
const metadataArray = Object.values(shape).map(fieldSchema =>
  filterRegistry.get(fieldSchema)
);
// Result: [{type: "select"}, {type: "select"}]
```

This works because the registry maps schema instances to their metadata, not property keys or paths. If you reuse the same schema instance, you'll get the same metadata object each time. If you want different metadata per field, you'll need to create separate schema instances and register each one with its own metadata.

You can read more about how registries and metadata work in Zod 4 in the [official docs](https://zod.dev/metadata) and see discussion of this behavior in [this issue](https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/issues/4681).

If this answers your question, feel free to close the issue!

