## 2. Adding metadata via `z.globalRegistry`, `.meta()`, and `.register()`

### 2.1. `z.globalRegistry` + `.meta()`

Zod v4 has a metadata/registry system. `z.globalRegistry` is a global registry that can store JSON Schema–style metadata like `id`, `title`, `description`, `examples`, etc. When you call `z.toJSONSchema()`, any metadata registered in `z.globalRegistry` is automatically included in the generated JSON Schema.

The `.meta()` method is a convenient way to both:

- register the schema in `z.globalRegistry`, and  
- attach arbitrary metadata that will be copied into the JSON Schema.

Example:

```ts
import * as z from "zod";

const emailSchema = z.string().meta({
  title: "Email address",
  description: "Your email address",
});

const jsonSchema = z.toJSONSchema(emailSchema);
// => { type: "string", title: "Email address", description: "Your email address", ... }
```

You can store any keys you want; they’ll be copied into the JSON Schema:

```ts
const schema = z.string().meta({
  whatever: 1234,
});

z.toJSONSchema(schema);
// => { type: "string", whatever: 1234 }
```

You can also use `.describe()` as a shorthand for `description`:

```ts
const Person = z.object({
  name: z.string().describe("The name of the person"),
  age: z.number().describe("The age in milliseconds since year 1337"),
});

// Descriptions appear in the JSON Schema:
z.toJSONSchema(Person);
// properties.name.description === "The name of the person"
// properties.age.description === "The age in milliseconds since year 1337"
```

`.describe("...")` is equivalent to `.meta({ description: "..." })` on that schema.

---

### 2.2. Custom registries and `.register()`

If you want more control or multiple registries (e.g., for different documentation layers or multiple OpenAPI files), you can create your own registry with `z.registry()` and use `.register()`:

```ts
import * as z from "zod";

const myRegistry = z.registry<{ title: string; description: string }>();

const emailSchema = z.string().email();

myRegistry.add(emailSchema, { title: "Email address", description: "..." });
myRegistry.get(emailSchema);
// => { title: "Email address", ... }
```

Instead of calling `add` directly, you can call `.register()` on the schema:

```ts
emailSchema.register(myRegistry, {
  title: "Email address",
  description: "...",
});
// returns the same schema instance
```

You can then pass a registry into `z.toJSONSchema()` to produce multiple interlinked JSON Schemas (e.g., for OpenAPI components):

```ts
const User = z.object({
  name: z.string(),
  get posts() {
    return z.array(Post);
  },
});

const Post = z.object({
  title: z.string(),
  content: z.string(),
  get author() {
    return User;
  },
});

z.globalRegistry.add(User, { id: "User" });
z.globalRegistry.add(Post, { id: "Post" });

const registrySchema = z.toJSONSchema(z.globalRegistry);
// => {
//   schemas: {
//     User: { id: 'User', type: 'object', ... },
//     Post: { id: 'Post', type: 'object', ... }
//   }
// }
```

To turn those `id`s into fully-qualified URLs for OpenAPI `$ref`s, use `uri`:

```ts
const registrySchemaWithUris = z.toJSONSchema(z.globalRegistry, {
  uri: (id) => `https://example.com/${id}.json`,
});
```

This is especially useful if you want each schema in its own file and to reference them across components in a large OpenAPI setup.

