The `items` property in the output of `z.treeifyError` is intentional and correctly models errors for array elements as an array of error trees, not an object. This structure is documented in the official Zod docs, and you should use optional chaining when accessing nested properties like `items` and `properties` to avoid runtime errors [[docs](https://zod.dev/error-formatting)].

The TypeScript error you're seeing usually happens when TypeScript can't infer the full type of the error tree—often because the generic parameter for `treeifyError` is lost or not specified. You can work around this by adding an explicit type annotation:

```ts
const treeErrors = z.treeifyError<typeof CustomerSchema>(state.error);
```

Or, if you know the expected structure, you can use a type assertion:

```ts
const treeErrors = z.treeifyError(state.error) as ZodErrorTree;
```

This will help TypeScript recognize the `items` property as an array. More details and workarounds are discussed in related issues [[example](https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/issues/4794)].

If you’re using Zod v3, you can also use the `.format()` method on the error object for a nested error structure. In Zod v4, `.format()` and `.flatten()` are deprecated in favor of `z.treeifyError()` [[changelog](https://zod.dev/v4/changelog)].

Let me know if this solves your problem or if you need more help! If your question is answered, please close the issue.


