When you do see `.refine()` errors in the result of `safeParse()`, Zod includes them in the error object's `issues` array, with each issue's `path` indicating the field (e.g., `["engagementPercentage"]`). There's no special mapping for object-level vs. field-level errors—both are present in the same array [docs](https://zod.dev/error-formatting).

If TanStack Form isn't displaying these errors, it may be because it only looks for errors at the top level or expects a specific error structure. Zod provides utilities like `z.treeifyError()` and `z.flattenError()` to convert the flat issues array into a nested or shallow object, which can help map errors to your form fields [docs](https://zod.dev/error-formatting).

If you want all errors (including cross-field or refinement errors) to show at once, the recommended workaround is to run base validations with Zod, then manually run your cross-field/refinement checks on the raw input, collect those errors, and merge them with the base validation errors before displaying them in the UI [see workaround](https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/issues/4738).

Let me know if you want a code example for this pattern, or if you have more questions about integrating with TanStack Form! If this answers your question, feel free to close the issue.


